<p><b>Principal component analysis</b> (<b>PCA</b>) is a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map" title=3D"Linear map">linear</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionality_reduction" title=3D"Dimens=
ionality reduction">dimensionality reduction</a> technique with application=
s in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exploratory_data_analysis" ti=
tle=3D"Exploratory data analysis">exploratory data analysis</a>, visualizat=
ion and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_preprocessing" title=
=3D"Data preprocessing">data preprocessing</a>.
</p><p>The data are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_map" ti=
tle=3D"Linear map">linearly transformed</a> onto a new <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordin=
ate system</a> such that the directions (principal components) capturing th=
e largest variation in the data can be easily identified.
</p><p>The <b>principal components</b> of a collection of points in a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_coordinate_space" title=3D"Real co=
ordinate space">real coordinate space</a> are a sequence of <span class=3D"=
mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-in=
line mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://w=
