<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_an=
alysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>PCA was invented in 1901 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kar=
l_Pearson" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_comp=
onent_analysis#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as an analogue of the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_axis_theorem" title=3D"Principal axi=
s theorem">principal axis theorem</a> in mechanics; it was later independen=
tly developed and named by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_=
Hotelling" title=3D"Harold Hotelling">Harold Hotelling</a> in the 1930s.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Depending on =
the field of application, it is also named the discrete <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karhunen%E2%80%93Lo%C3%A8ve_theorem" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Karhunen=E2=80=93Lo=C3=A8ve theorem">Karhunen=E2=80=93Lo=C3=
=A8ve</a> transform (KLT) in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signa=
l_processing" title=3D"Signal processing">signal processing</a>, the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Hotelling" title=3D"Harold Hotell=
ing">Hotelling</a> transform in multivariate quality control, <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proper_orthogonal_decomposition" title=3D"Prope=
r orthogonal decomposition">proper orthogonal decomposition</a> (POD) in me=
chanical engineering, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singular_val=
ue_decomposition" title=3D"Singular value decomposition">singular value dec=
omposition</a> (SVD) of <b>X</b> (invented in the last quarter of the 19th =
century<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>), <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigendecomposition" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Eigendecomposition">eigenvalue decomposition</a> (EVD) of <=
b>X</b><sup>T</sup><b>X</b> in linear algebra, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Factor_analysis" title=3D"Factor analysis">factor analysis</a>=
 (for a discussion of the differences between PCA and factor analysis see C=
h.&nbsp;7 of Jolliffe's <i>Principal Component Analysis</i>),<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Jolliffe2002_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Jolliffe2002-13"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eckart%E2%80%93Young_theorem" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eckart=E2=80=93Young theorem">Eckart=E2=80=
=93Young theorem</a> (Harman, 1960), or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Empirical_orthogonal_functions" title=3D"Empirical orthogonal functio=
ns">empirical orthogonal functions</a> (EOF) in meteorological science (Lor=
enz, 1956), empirical eigenfunction decomposition (Sirovich, 1987), quasiha=
rmonic modes (Brooks et al., 1988), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Spectral_theorem" title=3D"Spectral theorem">spectral decomposition</a> i=
n noise and vibration, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_sh=
ape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mode shape">empirical modal analysis</a=
> in structural dynamics.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Intuition">Intuition</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_componen=
t_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Intuit=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SCREE_plot.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/SCRE=
E_plot.jpg/250px-SCREE_plot.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"149" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"624" data-file-height=3D=
"372"></a><figcaption>A scree plot that is meant to help interpret the PCA =
and decide how many components to retain. The start of the bend in the line=
 (point of inflexion or "knee") should indicate how many components are ret=
ained, hence in this example, three factors should be retained.</figcaption=
></figure>
<p>PCA can be thought of as fitting a <i>p</i>-dimensional <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellipsoid" title=3D"Ellipsoid">ellipsoid</a> to th=
e data, where each axis of the ellipsoid represents a principal component. =
If some axis of the ellipsoid is small, then the variance along that axis i=
s also small.
</p><p>To find the axes of the ellipsoid, we must first center the values o=
f each variable in the dataset on 0 by subtracting the mean of the variable=
's observed values from each of those values. These transformed values are =
used instead of the original observed values for each of the variables. The=
n, we compute the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matri=
x" title=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance matrix</a> of the data and calcul=
ate the eigenvalues and corresponding eigenvectors of this covariance matri=
x. Then we must <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normalization_(sta=
tistics)" title=3D"Normalization (statistics)">normalize</a> each of the or=
thogonal eigenvectors to turn them into unit vectors. Once this is done, ea=
ch of the mutually-orthogonal unit eigenvectors can be interpreted as an ax=
is of the ellipsoid fitted to the data. This choice of basis will transform=
 the covariance matrix into a diagonalized form, in which the diagonal elem=
ents represent the variance of each axis. The proportion of the variance th=
at each eigenvector represents can be calculated by dividing the eigenvalue=
 corresponding to that eigenvector by the sum of all eigenvalues.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biplot" title=3D"Biplot">Bi=
plots</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scree_plot" title=3D=
"Scree plot">scree plots</a> (degree of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Explained_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Explained variance=
">explained variance</a>) are used to interpret findings of the PCA.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Details">Details</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_an=
alysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Details"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>PCA is defined as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal=
_transformation" title=3D"Orthogonal transformation">orthogonal</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_transformation" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Linear transformation">linear transformation</a> on a real <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inner_product_space" title=3D"Inner p=
roduct space">inner product space</a> that transforms the data to a new <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinat=
e system">coordinate system</a> such that the greatest variance by some sca=
lar projection of the data comes to lie on the first coordinate (called the=
 first principal component), the second greatest variance on the second coo=
rdinate, and so on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jolliffe2002_13-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#ci=
te_note-Jolliffe2002-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Consider an <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"=
><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displ=
ay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\=
displaystyle n\times p}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
