/wiki/Positive_semidefinite_matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive=
 semidefinite matrix">positive semidefinite matrix</a> such as <b>X</b><sup=
>T</sup><b>X</b> is that the quotient's maximum possible value is the large=
st <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalue</a> of the matrix, which occurs when <i>=
<b>w</b></i> is the corresponding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Eigenvector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvector">eigenvector</a>.
</p><p>With <b>w</b><sub>(1)</sub> found, the first principal component of =
a data vector <b>x</b><sub>(<i>i</i>)</sub> can then be given as a score <i=
>t</i><sub>1(<i>i</i>)</sub> =3D <b>x</b><sub>(<i>i</i>)</sub> =E2=8B=85 <b=
>w</b><sub>(1)</sub> in the transformed co-ordinates, or as the correspondi=
ng vector in the original variables, {<b>x</b><sub>(<i>i</i>)</sub> =E2=8B=
=85 <b>w</b><sub>(1)</sub>} <b>w</b><sub>(1)</sub>.
</p>
