 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The singular values (in <b>=CE=A3</b>) are the square roots of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalues</a> of the matrix <b>X</b><sup>T</sup><b>X</b>.=
 Each eigenvalue is proportional to the portion of the "variance" (more cor=
rectly of the sum of the squared distances of the points from their multidi=
mensional mean) that is associated with each eigenvector. The sum of all th=
e eigenvalues is equal to the sum of the squared distances of the points fr=
om their multidimensional mean. PCA essentially rotates the set of points a=
round their mean in order to align with the principal components. This move=
s as much of the variance as possible (using an orthogonal transformation) =
into the first few dimensions. The values in the remaining dimensions, ther=
efore, tend to be small and may be dropped with minimal loss of information=
 (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle_Component_Analysis=
#PCA_and_information_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Principle Compo=
nent Analysis">below</a>). PCA is often used in this manner for <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionality_reduction" title=3D"Dimensiona=
lity reduction">dimensionality reduction</a>. PCA has the distinction of be=
ing the optimal orthogonal transformation for keeping the subspace that has=
 largest "variance" (as defined above). This advantage, however, comes at t=
he price of greater computational requirements if compared, for example, an=
d when applicable, to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete=
_cosine_transform" title=3D"Discrete cosine transform">discrete cosine tran=
sform</a>, and in particular to the DCT-II which is simply known as the "DC=
T". <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_dimensionality_reduc=
tion" title=3D"Nonlinear dimensionality reduction">Nonlinear dimensionality=
 reduction</a> techniques tend to be more computationally demanding than PC=
A.
</p><p>PCA is sensitive to the scaling of the variables. Mathematically thi=
s sensitivity comes from the way a rescaling changes the sample=E2=80=91cov=
ariance matrix that PCA diagonalises.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Holmes2023_14-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compo=
nent_analysis#cite_note-Holmes2023-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Let <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span c=
