<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Limitations">Limitations</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_comp=
onent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: L=
imitations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>As noted above, the results of PCA depend on the scaling of the variable=
s. This can be cured by scaling each feature by its standard deviation, so =
that one ends up with dimensionless features with unital variance.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Leznik_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Leznik-19"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The applicability of PCA as described above is limited by certain (t=
acit) assumptions<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-20"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> made in its derivation. In particular, PCA can capture linear correl=
ations between the features but fails when this assumption is violated (see=
 Figure 6a in the reference). In some cases, coordinate transformations can=
 restore the linearity assumption and PCA can then be applied (see <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kernel_principal_component_analysis" titl=
e=3D"Kernel principal component analysis">kernel PCA</a>).
</p><p>Another limitation is the mean-removal process before constructing t=
he covariance matrix for PCA. In fields such as astronomy, all the signals =
are non-negative, and the mean-removal process will force the mean of some =
astrophysical exposures to be zero, which consequently creates unphysical n=
egative fluxes,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-soummer12_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note=
-soummer12-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> and forward modeling has to be performed to reco=
ver the true magnitude of the signals.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-pueyo16_22-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compone=
nt_analysis#cite_note-pueyo16-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> As an alternative method, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-negative_matrix_factorization" ti=
tle=3D"Non-negative matrix factorization">non-negative matrix factorization=
</a> focusing only on the non-negative elements in the matrices is well-sui=
ted for astrophysical observations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-blantonRoweis07_23-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_co=
mponent_analysis#cite_note-blantonRoweis07-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-zhu16_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-zhu16-24"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-ren18_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-ren18-25"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> See more a=
t <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#Non=
-negative_matrix_factorization">the relation between PCA and non-negative m=
atrix factorization</a>.
</p><p>PCA is at a disadvantage if the data has not been standardized befor=
e applying the algorithm to it. PCA transforms the original data into data =
that is relevant to the principal components of that data, which means that=
 the new data variables cannot be interpreted in the same ways that the ori=
ginals were. They are linear interpretations of the original variables. Als=
o, if PCA is not performed properly, there is a high likelihood of informat=
ion loss.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-26"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>PCA relies on a linear model. If a dataset has a pattern hidden insi=
de it that is nonlinear, then PCA can actually steer the analysis in the co=
mplete opposite direction of progress.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-abbott_27-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_componen=
t_analysis#cite_note-abbott-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Tem=
plate" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citing sources"><span t=
itle=3D"This citation requires a reference to the specific page or range of=
 pages in which the material appears. (June 2021)">page&nbsp;needed</span><=
/a></i>]</sup> Researchers at Kansas State University discovered that the s=
ampling error in their experiments impacted the bias of PCA results. "If th=
e number of subjects or blocks is smaller than 30, and/or the researcher is=
 interested in PC's beyond the first, it may be better to first correct for=
 the serial correlation, before PCA is conducted".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-jiang=
_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princip=
al_component_analysis#cite_note-jiang-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The researchers at Ka=
nsas State also found that PCA could be "seriously biased if the autocorrel=
ation structure of the data are not correctly handled".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
jiang_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
incipal_component_analysis#cite_note-jiang-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"PCA_and_information_theory"=
>PCA and information theory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: PCA and information theory"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Dimensionality reduction results in a loss of information, in general. P=
CA-based dimensionality reduction tends to minimize that information loss, =
under certain signal and noise models.
</p><p>Under the assumption that
