></span>.
</p><p>This is very constructive, as cov(<b>X</b>) is guaranteed to be a no=
n-negative definite matrix and thus is guaranteed to be diagonalisable by s=
ome unitary matrix.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Covariance-free_computation=
">Covariance-free computation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Covariance-free computation"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In practical implementations, especially with <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/High_dimensional_data" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"High d=
imensional data">high dimensional data</a> (large <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>), the naive covariance method is =
rarely used because it is not efficient due to high computational and memor=
y costs of explicitly determining the covariance matrix. The covariance-fre=
e approach avoids the <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>np</i><sup>2</sup></span> =
operations of explicitly calculating and storing the covariance matrix <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>X</b></span>, instead utilizing one of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix-free_methods" title=3D"Matr=
ix-free methods">matrix-free methods</a>, for example, based on the functio=
n evaluating the product <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>(X r)</b><=
/span> at the cost of <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>np</i></span> operations.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Iterative_computation">Iter=
ative computation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Iterative computation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One way to compute the first principal component efficiently<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-roweis_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-roweis-41"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is sho=
wn in the following pseudo-code, for a data matrix <span class=3D"texhtml">=
<b>X</b></span> with zero mean, without ever computing its covariance matri=
x.
</p>
<pre><span class=3D"texhtml"><b>r</b></span> =3D a random vector of length =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>
<b>r</b> =3D <b>r</b> / norm(<b>r</b>)
do <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span> times=
:
      <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>s</b> =3D 0</span> (a vector of length <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>)
      <span class=3D"nowrap">for each row <b>x</b> in <b>X</b></span>
            <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>s</b> =3D <b>s</b> + (<b>x</b> =E2=8B=
=85 <b>r</b>) <b>x</b></span>
      <span class=3D"nowrap">=CE=BB =3D <b>r</b><sup>T</sup><b>s</b></span>=
 <span class=3D"nowrap">// =CE=BB is the eigenvalue</span>
      <span class=3D"nowrap">error =3D |=CE=BB =E2=8B=85 <b>r</b> =E2=88=92=
 <b>s</b>|</span>
      <span class=3D"nowrap"><b>r</b> =3D <b>s</b> / norm(<b>s</b>)</span>
      <span class=3D"nowrap">exit if error &lt; tolerance</span>
return <span class=3D"nowrap">=CE=BB, <b>r</b></span>
</pre>
<p>This <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_iteration" title=3D"=
Power iteration">power iteration</a> algorithm simply calculates the vector=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>(X r)</b></span>, normalizes, and =
places the result back in <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>r</b></span>. The eige=
nvalue is approximated by <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>r<sup>T</sup> (X<sup>T=
</sup>X) r</b></span>, which is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Rayleigh_quotient" title=3D"Rayleigh quotient">Rayleigh quotient</a> on t=
he unit vector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>r</b></span> for the covariance m=
atrix <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>X </b></span>. If the largest=
 singular value is well separated from the next largest one, the vector <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><b>r</b></span> gets close to the first principal comp=
onent of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>X</b></span> within the number of itera=
tions <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">c</span>, w=
hich is small relative to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">p</span>, at the total cost <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>2cnp</i></s=
pan>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_iteration" title=
=3D"Power iteration">power iteration</a> convergence can be accelerated wit=
hout noticeably sacrificing the small cost per iteration using more advance=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix-free_methods" title=3D"Ma=
trix-free methods">matrix-free methods</a>, such as the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lanczos_algorithm" title=3D"Lanczos algorithm">Lanczo=
s algorithm</a> or the Locally Optimal Block Preconditioned Conjugate Gradi=
ent (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LOBPCG" title=3D"LOBPCG">LOBP=
CG</a>) method.
</p><p>Subsequent principal components can be computed one-by-one via defla=
tion or simultaneously as a block. In the former approach, imprecisions in =
already computed approximate principal components additively affect the acc=
uracy of the subsequently computed principal components, thus increasing th=
e error with every new computation. The latter approach in the block power =
method replaces single-vectors <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>r</b></span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>s</b></span> with block-vectors, matrices <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>S</b></spa=
n>. Every column of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>R</b></span> approximates on=
e of the leading principal components, while all columns are iterated simul=
taneously. The main calculation is evaluation of the product <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>(X R)</b></span>. Implemented, for example, in <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LOBPCG" title=3D"LOBPCG">LOBPCG</a>,=
 efficient blocking eliminates the accumulation of the errors, allows using=
 high-level <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BLAS" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"BLAS">BLAS</a> matrix-matrix product functions, and typicall=
y leads to faster convergence, compared to the single-vector one-by-one tec=
hnique.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"The_NIPALS_method">The NIPA=
LS method</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPr=
incipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edi=
t section: The NIPALS method"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><i>Non-linear iterative partial least squares (NIPALS)</i> is a variant =
the classical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_iteration" tit=
le=3D"Power iteration">power iteration</a> with matrix deflation by subtrac=
tion implemented for computing the first few components in a principal comp=
onent or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_least_squares" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Partial least squares">partial least squares</=
a> analysis. For very-high-dimensional datasets, such as those generated in=
 the *omics sciences (for example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Genomics" title=3D"Genomics">genomics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Metabolomics" title=3D"Metabolomics">metabolomics</a>) it is usua=
lly only necessary to compute the first few PCs. The <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-linear_iterative_partial_least_squares" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Non-linear iterative partial least squares">non-linear i=
terative partial least squares</a> (NIPALS) algorithm updates iterative app=
roximations to the leading scores and loadings <b>t</b><sub>1</sub> and <b>=
r</b><sub>1</sub><sup>T</sup> by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Power_iteration" title=3D"Power iteration">power iteration</a> multiplyi=
ng on every iteration by <b>X</b> on the left and on the right, that is, ca=
lculation of the covariance matrix is avoided, just as in the matrix-free i=
mplementation of the power iterations to <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T=
</sup>X</b></span>, based on the function evaluating the product <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml"><b>X<sup>T</sup>(X r)</b> =3D <b>((X r)<sup>T</sup>X)<sup>T</=
sup></b></span>.
</p><p>The matrix deflation by subtraction is performed by subtracting the =
outer product, <b>t</b><sub>1</sub><b>r</b><sub>1</sub><sup>T</sup> from <b=
>X</b> leaving the deflated residual matrix used to calculate the subsequen=
t leading PCs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-42"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
For large data matrices, or matrices that have a high degree of column coll=
inearity, NIPALS suffers from loss of orthogonality of PCs due to machine p=
recision <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Round-off_errors" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Round-off errors">round-off errors</a> accumulate=
d in each iteration and matrix deflation by subtraction.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal=
_component_analysis#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Gram%E2%80%93Schmidt" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gram=E2=
=80=93Schmidt">Gram=E2=80=93Schmidt</a> re-orthogonalization algorithm is a=
pplied to both the scores and the loadings at each iteration step to elimin=
ate this loss of orthogonality.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_=
note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> NIPALS reliance on single-vector multiplications canno=
t take advantage of high-level <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BLA=
S" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"BLAS">BLAS</a> and results in slow conver=
gence for clustered leading singular values=E2=80=94both these deficiencies=
 are resolved in more sophisticated matrix-free block solvers, such as the =
Locally Optimal Block Preconditioned Conjugate Gradient (<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LOBPCG" title=3D"LOBPCG">LOBPCG</a>) method.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Online/sequential_estimatio=
n"><span id=3D"Online.2Fsequential_estimation"></span>Online/sequential est=
imation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrin=
cipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit =
section: Online/sequential estimation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In an "online" or "streaming" situation with data arriving piece by piec=
e rather than being stored in a single batch, it is useful to make an estim=
ate of the PCA projection that can be updated sequentially. This can be don=
e efficiently, but requires different algorithms.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compon=
ent_analysis#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Qualitative_variables">Qual=
itative variables</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Qualitative variables"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In PCA, it is common that we want to introduce qualitative variables as =
supplementary elements. For example, many quantitative variables have been =
measured on plants. For these plants, some qualitative variables are availa=
ble as, for example, the species to which the plant belongs. These data wer=
e subjected to PCA for quantitative variables. When analyzing the results, =
it is natural to connect the principal components to the qualitative variab=
le <i>species</i>.
For this, the following results are produced.
</p>
<ul><li>Identification, on the factorial planes, of the different species, =
for example, using different colors.</li>
<li>Representation, on the factorial planes, of the centers of gravity of p=
lants belonging to the same species.</li>
<li>For each center of gravity and each axis, p-value to judge the signific=
ance of the difference between the center of gravity and origin.</li></ul>
<p>These results are what is called <i>introducing a qualitative variable a=
s supplementary element</i>. This procedure is detailed in and Husson, L=C3=
=AA, &amp; Pag=C3=A8s (2009) and Pag=C3=A8s (2013).
Few software offer this option in an "automatic" way. This is the case of <=
a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"http://www.coheris.com/p=
roduits/analytics/logiciel-data-mining/">SPAD</a> that historically, follow=
ing the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludovic_Lebart" ti=
tle=3D"Ludovic Lebart">Ludovic Lebart</a>, was the first to propose this op=
tion, and the R package <a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D=
"http://factominer.free.fr/">FactoMineR</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_co=
mponent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D23" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Intelligence">Intelligence<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_co=
mponent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D24" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Intelligence"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>The earliest application of factor analysis was in locating and measurin=
g components of human intelligence. It was believed that intelligence had v=
arious uncorrelated components such as spatial intelligence, verbal intelli=
gence, induction, deduction etc and that scores on these could be adduced b=
y factor analysis from results on various tests, to give a single index kno=
wn as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence_quotient" t=
itle=3D"Intelligence quotient">Intelligence Quotient</a> (IQ). The pioneeri=
ng statistical psychologist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charle=
s_Spearman" title=3D"Charles Spearman">Spearman</a> actually developed fact=
or analysis in 1904 for his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-fa=
ctor_theory_of_intelligence" title=3D"Two-factor theory of intelligence">tw=
o-factor theory</a> of intelligence, adding a formal technique to the scien=
ce of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychometrics" title=3D"Psyc=
hometrics">psychometrics</a>. In 1924 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Louis_Leon_Thurstone" title=3D"Louis Leon Thurstone">Thurstone</a> look=
ed for 56 factors of intelligence, developing the notion of Mental Age. Sta=
ndard IQ tests today are based on this early work.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kapla=
n,_R.M._2010_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Kaplan,_R.M._2010-46"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Residential_differentiation=
">Residential differentiation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: Residential differentiation"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1949, Shevky and Williams introduced the theory of <b>factorial ecolo=
gy</b>, which dominated studies of residential differentiation from the 195=
0s to the 1970s.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-47"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> Neighbourhoods in a city were recognizable or could be distinguished =
from one another by various characteristics which could be reduced to three=
 by factor analysis. These were known as 'social rank' (an index of occupat=
ional status), 'familism' or family size, and 'ethnicity'; Cluster analysis=
 could then be applied to divide the city into clusters or precincts accord=
ing to values of the three key factor variables. An extensive literature de=
veloped around factorial ecology in urban geography, but the approach went =
out of fashion after 1980 as being methodologically primitive and having li=
ttle place in postmodern geographical paradigms.
</p><p>One of the problems with factor analysis has always been finding con=
vincing names for the various artificial factors. In 2000, Flood revived th=
e factorial ecology approach to show that principal components analysis act=
ually gave meaningful answers directly, without resorting to factor rotatio=
n. The principal components were actually dual variables or shadow prices o=
f 'forces' pushing people together or apart in cities. The first component =
was 'accessibility', the classic trade-off between demand for travel and de=
mand for space, around which classical urban economics is based. The next t=
wo components were 'disadvantage', which keeps people of similar status in =
separate neighbourhoods (mediated by planning), and ethnicity, where people=
 of similar ethnic backgrounds try to co-locate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compone=
nt_analysis#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>About the same time, the Australian Bureau of Statistics defined dis=
tinct indexes of advantage and disadvantage taking the first principal comp=
onent of sets of key variables that were thought to be important. These SEI=
FA indexes are regularly published for various jurisdictions, and are used =
frequently in spatial analysis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_=
note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Development_indexes">Develo=
pment indexes</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=
=3D"Edit section: Development indexes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>PCA can be used as a formal method for the development of indexes. As an=
 alternative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confirmatory_composit=
e_analysis" title=3D"Confirmatory composite analysis">confirmatory composit=
e analysis</a> has been proposed to develop and assess indexes.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pr=
incipal_component_analysis#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The City Development Index was developed by PCA from about 200 indic=
ators of city outcomes in a 1996 survey of 254 global cities. The first pri=
ncipal component was subject to iterative regression, adding the original v=
ariables singly until about 90% of its variation was accounted for. The ind=
ex ultimately used about 15 indicators but was a good predictor of many mor=
e variables. Its comparative value agreed very well with a subjective asses=
sment of the condition of each city. The coefficients on items of infrastru=
cture were roughly proportional to the average costs of providing the under=
lying services, suggesting the Index was actually a measure of effective ph=
ysical and social investment in the city.
</p><p>The country-level <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Dev=
elopment_Index" title=3D"Human Development Index">Human Development Index</=
a> (HDI) from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Nations_Devel=
opment_Programme" title=3D"United Nations Development Programme">UNDP</a>, =
which has been published since 1990 and is very extensively used in develop=
ment studies,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-51"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> has very similar coefficients on similar indicators, strongly suggesting=
 it was originally constructed using PCA.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Population_genetics">Popula=
tion genetics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=
=3D"Edit section: Population genetics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In 1978 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luigi_Luca_Cavalli-Sfor=
za" title=3D"Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza">Cavalli-Sforza</a> and others pione=
ered the use of principal components analysis (PCA) to summarise data on va=
riation in human gene frequencies across regions. The components showed dis=
tinctive patterns, including gradients and sinusoidal waves. They interpret=
ed these patterns as resulting from specific ancient migration events.
</p><p>Since then, PCA has been ubiquitous in population genetics, with tho=
usands of papers using PCA as a display mechanism. Genetics varies largely =
according to proximity, so the first two principal components actually show=
 spatial distribution and may be used to map the relative geographical loca=
tion of different population groups, thereby showing individuals who have w=
andered from their original locations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-52" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysi=
s#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>PCA in genetics has been technically controversial, in that the tech=
nique has been performed on discrete non-normal variables and often on bina=
ry allele markers. The lack of any measures of standard error in PCA are al=
so an impediment to more consistent usage. In August 2022, the molecular bi=
ologist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eran_Elhaik" title=3D"Eran=
 Elhaik">Eran Elhaik</a> published a theoretical paper in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_Reports" title=3D"Scientific Reports">Sc=
ientific Reports</a> analyzing 12 PCA applications. He concluded that it wa=
s easy to manipulate the method, which, in his view, generated results that=
 were 'erroneous, contradictory, and absurd.' Specifically, he argued, the =
results achieved in population genetics were characterized by cherry-pickin=
g and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_reasoning" title=3D=
"Circular reasoning">circular reasoning</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component=
_analysis#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Market_research_and_indexes=
_of_attitude">Market research and indexes of attitude</h3><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Market research and =
indexes of attitude"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Market research has been an extensive user of PCA. It is used to develop=
 customer satisfaction or customer loyalty scores for products, and with cl=
ustering, to develop market segments that may be targeted with advertising =
campaigns, in much the same way as factorial ecology will locate geographic=
al areas with similar characteristics.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysi=
s#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>PCA rapidly transforms large amounts of data into smaller, easier-to=
-digest variables that can be more rapidly and readily analyzed. In any con=
sumer questionnaire, there are series of questions designed to elicit consu=
mer attitudes, and principal components seek out latent variables underlyin=
g these attitudes. For example, the Oxford Internet Survey in 2013 asked 20=
00 people about their attitudes and beliefs, and from these analysts extrac=
ted four principal component dimensions, which they identified as 'escape',=
 'social networking', 'efficiency', and 'problem creating'.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princi=
pal_component_analysis#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another example from Joe Flood in 2008 extracted an attitudinal inde=
x toward housing from 28 attitude questions in a national survey of 2697 ho=
useholds in Australia. The first principal component represented a general =
attitude toward property and home ownership. The index, or the attitude que=
stions it embodied, could be fed into a General Linear Model of tenure choi=
ce. The strongest determinant of private renting by far was the attitude in=
dex, rather than income, marital status or household type.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princip=
al_component_analysis#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Quantitative_finance">Quant=
itative finance</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=
=3D"Edit section: Quantitative finance"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantitative_finance" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantitative finance">quantitative finance</a>, P=
CA is used<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Miller_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Miller-=
57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_risk_management" titl=
e=3D"Financial risk management">financial risk management</a>, and has been=
 applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Financial_modeling#Qua=
ntitative_finance" title=3D"Financial modeling">other problems</a> such as =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portfolio_optimization" title=3D"P=
ortfolio optimization">portfolio optimization</a>.
</p><p>PCA is commonly used in problems involving <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Fixed_income" title=3D"Fixed income">fixed income</a> secur=
ities and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_fund" title=3D"Bond=
 fund">portfolios</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interes=
t_rate_derivative" title=3D"Interest rate derivative">interest rate derivat=
ives</a>.=20
Valuations here depend on the entire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Yield_curve" title=3D"Yield curve">yield curve</a>, comprising numerous =
highly correlated instruments, and PCA is used to define a set of component=
s or factors that explain rate movements,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hull_58-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_compone=
nt_analysis#cite_note-Hull-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
thereby facilitating the modelling.
One common risk management application is to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Value_at_risk#Computation_methods" title=3D"Value at risk">calcu=
lating value at risk</a>, VaR, applying PCA to the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_methods_in_finance" title=3D"Monte Carlo metho=
ds in finance">Monte Carlo simulation</a>.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-59" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-59"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Here, for each simulation-sample, the components are stressed, and rates, a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monte_Carlo_methods_for_option_=
pricing#Methodology" title=3D"Monte Carlo methods for option pricing">in tu=
rn option values</a>, are then reconstructed;=20
with VaR calculated, finally, over the entire run.=20
PCA is also used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hedge_(finance=
)" title=3D"Hedge (finance)">hedging</a> exposure to <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Interest_rate_risk" title=3D"Interest rate risk">interes=
t rate risk</a>, given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_rate_du=
ration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Key rate duration">partial durations=
</a> and other sensitivities.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hull_58-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Hull-58"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
Under both, the first three, typically, principal components of the system =
are of interest (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed-income_attr=
ibution#Modeling_the_yield_curve" title=3D"Fixed-income attribution">repres=
enting</a> "shift", "twist", and "curvature").
These principal components are derived from an eigen-decomposition of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix" title=3D"Covaria=
nce matrix">covariance matrix</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Yield_curve" title=3D"Yield curve">yield</a> at predefined maturities;=
=20
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-60" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-60"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"V=
ariance">variance</a> of each component is its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenva=
lue</a> (and as the components are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Orthogonal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orthogonal">orthogonal</a>, no =
correlation need be incorporated in subsequent modelling).
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equity_(finance)" title=
=3D"Equity (finance)">equity</a>, an optimal portfolio is one where the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_return" title=3D"Expected re=
turn">expected return</a> is maximized for a given level of risk, or altern=
atively, where risk is minimized for a given return; see <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markowitz_model" title=3D"Markowitz model">Markowitz=
 model</a> for discussion.
Thus, one approach is to reduce portfolio risk, where <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asset_allocation" title=3D"Asset allocation">allocation=
 strategies</a> are applied to the "principal portfolios" instead of the un=
derlying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_stock" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Capital stock">stocks</a>.
A second approach is to enhance portfolio return, using the principal compo=
nents to select companies' stocks with upside potential.
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
PCA has also been used to understand relationships <sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mill=
er_57-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis#cite_note-Miller-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> between internatio=
nal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equity_market" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Equity market">equity markets</a>, and within markets betwe=
en groups of companies in industries or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Stock_market_index#Types_of_indices_by_coverage" title=3D"Stock marke=
t index">sectors</a>.
</p><p>PCA may also be applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Stress_test_(financial)" title=3D"Stress test (financial)">stress testing</=
a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IMF_63-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-IMF-63"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> essentially an analysis of a bank's ability to endure <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_bank_stress_tests" title=3D"List of bank str=
ess tests">a hypothetical adverse economic scenario</a>. Its utility is in =
"distilling the information contained in [several] <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Macroeconomic_model" title=3D"Macroeconomic model">macroec=
onomic variables</a> into a more manageable data set, which can then [be us=
ed] for analysis."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IMF_63-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-IM=
F-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Here, the resulting factors are linked to e.g. interest r=
ates =E2=80=93 based on the largest elements of the factor's <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eige=
nvector">eigenvector</a> =E2=80=93 and it is then observed how a "shock" to=
 each of the factors affects the implied assets of each of the banks.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Neuroscience">Neuroscience<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_co=
mponent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Neuroscience"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>A variant of principal components analysis is used in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuroscience" title=3D"Neuroscience">neuroscience</a=
> to identify the specific properties of a stimulus that increases a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neuron" title=3D"Neuron">neuron</a>'s pr=
obability of generating an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_=
potential" title=3D"Action potential">action potential</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-64" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princi=
pal_component_analysis#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-brenner=
00_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis#cite_note-brenner00-65"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This technique =
is known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spike-triggered_covari=
ance" title=3D"Spike-triggered covariance">spike-triggered covariance analy=
sis</a>. In a typical application an experimenter presents a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_noise" title=3D"White noise">white noise</=
a> process as a stimulus (usually either as a sensory input to a test subje=
ct, or as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" titl=
e=3D"Electric current">current</a> injected directly into the neuron) and r=
ecords a train of action potentials, or spikes, produced by the neuron as a=
 result. Presumably, certain features of the stimulus make the neuron more =
likely to spike. In order to extract these features, the experimenter calcu=
lates the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix" title=
=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance matrix</a> of the <i>spike-triggered ense=
mble</i>, the set of all stimuli (defined and discretized over a finite tim=
e window, typically on the order of 100 ms) that immediately preceded a spi=
ke. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvectors_and_eigenvalu=
es" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvectors and eigenvalues">eigenvecto=
rs</a> of the difference between the spike-triggered covariance matrix and =
the covariance matrix of the <i>prior stimulus ensemble</i> (the set of all=
 stimuli, defined over the same length time window) then indicate the direc=
tions in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_space" title=
=3D"Vector space">space</a> of stimuli along which the variance of the spik=
e-triggered ensemble differed the most from that of the prior stimulus ense=
mble. Specifically, the eigenvectors with the largest positive eigenvalues =
correspond to the directions along which the variance of the spike-triggere=
d ensemble showed the largest positive change compared to the variance of t=
he prior. Since these were the directions in which varying the stimulus led=
 to a spike, they are often good approximations of the sought after relevan=
t stimulus features.
</p><p>In neuroscience, PCA is also used to discern the identity of a neuro=
n from the shape of its action potential. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Spike_sorting" title=3D"Spike sorting">Spike sorting</a> is an impo=
rtant procedure because <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrophy=
siology#Extracellular_recording" title=3D"Electrophysiology">extracellular<=
/a> recording techniques often pick up signals from more than one neuron. I=
n spike sorting, one first uses PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the spa=
ce of action potential waveforms, and then performs <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis" title=3D"Cluster analysis">clustering a=
nalysis</a> to associate specific action potentials with individual neurons=
.
</p><p>PCA as a dimension reduction technique is particularly suited to det=
ect coordinated activities of large neuronal ensembles. It has been used in=
 determining collective variables, that is, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Order_parameters" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Order parameters=
">order parameters</a>, during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pha=
se_transitions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Phase transitions">phase tra=
nsitions</a> in the brain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-66" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-=
66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relation_with_other_methods=
">Relation with other methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Relation with other methods"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Correspondence_analysis">Co=
rrespondence analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32" =
title=3D"Edit section: Correspondence analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correspondence_analysis" title=
=3D"Correspondence analysis">Correspondence analysis</a> (CA)
was developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Paul_Benz%C3=
%A9cri" title=3D"Jean-Paul Benz=C3=A9cri">Jean-Paul Benz=C3=A9cri</a><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-67" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and is conceptually similar to PCA, but scales the data (which should be no=
n-negative) so that rows and columns are treated equivalently. It is tradit=
ionally applied to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contingency_tab=
les" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Contingency tables">contingency tables<=
/a>.
CA decomposes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_stat=
istic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chi-squared statistic">chi-squared st=
atistic</a> associated to this table into orthogonal factors.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prin=
cipal_component_analysis#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Because CA is a descriptive technique, it can be applied to tables for whic=
h the chi-squared statistic is appropriate or not.
Several variants of CA are available including <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Detrended_correspondence_analysis" title=3D"Detrended correspo=
ndence analysis">detrended correspondence analysis</a> and <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canonical_correspondence_analysis" title=3D"Canoni=
cal correspondence analysis">canonical correspondence analysis</a>. One spe=
cial extension is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_corresp=
ondence_analysis" title=3D"Multiple correspondence analysis">multiple corre=
spondence analysis</a>, which may be seen as the counterpart of principal c=
omponent analysis for categorical data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analys=
is#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Factor_analysis">Factor ana=
lysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrinci=
pal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Factor analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:PCA_versus_Factor_Analysis.jpg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/2/29/PCA_versus_Factor_Analysis.jpg/250px-PCA_versus_Factor_Analysis=
.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"288" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"494" data-file-height=3D"570"></a><figcaption>The a=
bove picture is an example of the difference between PCA and Factor Analysi=
s. In the top diagram the "factor" (e.g., career path) represents the three=
 observed variables (e.g., doctor, lawyer, teacher) whereas in the bottom d=
iagram the observed variables (e.g., pre-school teacher, middle school teac=
her, high school teacher) are reduced into the component of interest (e.g.,=
 teacher).</figcaption></figure>
<p>Principal component analysis creates variables that are linear combinati=
ons of the original variables. The new variables have the property that the=
 variables are all orthogonal. The PCA transformation can be helpful as a p=
re-processing step before clustering. PCA is a variance-focused approach se=
eking to reproduce the total variable variance, in which components reflect=
 both common and unique variance of the variable. PCA is generally preferre=
d for purposes of data reduction (that is, translating variable space into =
optimal factor space) but not when the goal is to detect the latent constru=
ct or factors.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor_analysis" title=3D"F=
actor analysis">Factor analysis</a> is similar to principal component analy=
sis, in that factor analysis also involves linear combinations of variables=
. Different from PCA, factor analysis is a correlation-focused approach see=
king to reproduce the inter-correlations among variables, in which the fact=
ors "represent the common variance of variables, excluding unique variance"=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In terms =
of the correlation matrix, this corresponds with focusing on explaining the=
 off-diagonal terms (that is, shared co-variance), while PCA focuses on exp=
laining the terms that sit on the diagonal. However, as a side result, when=
 trying to reproduce the on-diagonal terms, PCA also tends to fit relativel=
y well the off-diagonal correlations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jolliffe2002_13-4"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_com=
ponent_analysis#cite_note-Jolliffe2002-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referen=
ce nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 158">:=E2=80=8A158=E2=80=8A</spa=
n></sup> Results given by PCA and factor analysis are very similar in most =
situations, but this is not always the case, and there are some problems wh=
ere the results are significantly different. Factor analysis is generally u=
sed when the research purpose is detecting data structure (that is, latent =
constructs or factors) or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causal_m=
odeling" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Causal modeling">causal modeling</a=
>. If the factor model is incorrectly formulated or the assumptions are not=
 met, then factor analysis will give erroneous results.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_=
component_analysis#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"K-means_clustering"><span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><var>K</var></span>-means clustering</h3><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D34" title=3D"Edit section: K-means clustering">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>It has been asserted that the relaxed solution of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/K-means_clustering" title=3D"K-means clustering"><span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><var>k</var></span>-means clustering</a>, specified by the=
 cluster indicators, is given by the principal components, and the PCA subs=
pace spanned by the principal directions is identical to the cluster centro=
id subspace.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-72"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, =
that PCA is a useful relaxation of <span class=3D"texhtml"><var>k</var></sp=
an>-means clustering was not a new result,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-74" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_ana=
lysis#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and it is straightforward to uncover counte=
rexamples to the statement that the cluster centroid subspace is spanned by=
 the principal directions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-=
75"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Non-negative_matrix_factori=
zation">Non-negative matrix factorization</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D35" title=3D"Edit section: Non-negative matrix factorizatio=
n"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Fractional_Residual_Variances_comparison,_PCA_and_NMF.pdf" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/f/f2/Fractional_Residual_Variances_comparison%2C_PCA_and_NMF.pdf/pa=
ge1-500px-Fractional_Residual_Variances_comparison%2C_PCA_and_NMF.pdf.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"500" height=3D"245" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"1185" data-file-height=3D"581"></a><figcaption>Fractional=
 residual variance (FRV) plots for PCA and NMF;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ren18_25=
-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_=
component_analysis#cite_note-ren18-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> for PCA, the theoretical=
 values are the contribution from the residual eigenvalues. In comparison, =
the FRV curves for PCA reaches a flat plateau where no signal are captured =
effectively; while the NMF FRV curves decline continuously, indicating a be=
tter ability to capture signal. The FRV curves for NMF also converges to hi=
gher levels than PCA, indicating the less-overfitting property of NMF.</fig=
caption></figure> <p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-negative_=
matrix_factorization" title=3D"Non-negative matrix factorization">Non-negat=
ive matrix factorization</a> (NMF) is a dimension reduction method where on=
ly non-negative elements in the matrices are used, which is therefore a pro=
mising method in astronomy,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-blantonRoweis07_23-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component=
_analysis#cite_note-blantonRoweis07-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-zhu1=
6_24-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princi=
pal_component_analysis#cite_note-zhu16-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-r=
en18_25-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pri=
ncipal_component_analysis#cite_note-ren18-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> in the sense that=
 astrophysical signals are non-negative. The PCA components are orthogonal =
to each other, while the NMF components are all non-negative and therefore =
constructs a non-orthogonal basis.
</p><p>In PCA, the contribution of each component is ranked based on the ma=
gnitude of its corresponding eigenvalue, which is equivalent to the fractio=
nal residual variance (FRV) in analyzing empirical data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-soummer12_21-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-soummer12-21"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For NMF=
, its components are ranked based only on the empirical FRV curves.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-ren18_25-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-ren18-25"><span class=3D"=
