<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Iconography_of_correlations=
">Iconography of correlations</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DPrincipal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D36" title=3D"Edit section: Iconography of correlations"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is often difficult to interpret the principal components when the dat=
a include many variables of various origins, or when some variables are qua=
litative. This leads the PCA user to a delicate elimination of several vari=
ables. If observations or variables have an excessive impact on the directi=
on of the axes, they should be removed and then projected as supplementary =
elements. In addition, it is necessary to avoid interpreting the proximitie=
s between the points close to the center of the factorial plane.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:AirMerIconographyCorrelation.jpg" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commo=
ns/thumb/b/b3/AirMerIconographyCorrelation.jpg/250px-AirMerIconographyCorre=
lation.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"231" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"544" data-file-height=3D"503"></a><figcaption=
>Iconography of correlations =E2=80=93 Geochemistry of marine aerosols</fig=
caption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iconography_of_correlations=
" title=3D"Iconography of correlations">iconography of correlations</a>, on=
 the contrary, which is not a projection on a system of axes, does not have=
 these drawbacks. We can therefore keep all the variables.
</p><p>The principle of the diagram is to underline the "remarkable" correl=
ations of the correlation matrix, by a solid line (positive correlation) or=
 dotted line (negative correlation).
</p><p>A strong correlation is not "remarkable" if it is not direct, but ca=
used by the effect of a third variable. Conversely, weak correlations can b=
e "remarkable". For example, if a variable Y depends on several independent=
 variables, the correlations of Y with each of them are weak and yet "remar=
kable".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Generalizations">Generaliza=
tions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrinci=
pal_component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Generalizations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sparse_PCA">Sparse PCA</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_compon=
ent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit section: Spa=
rse PCA"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_PCA" title=3D=
"Sparse PCA">Sparse PCA</a></div>
<p>A particular disadvantage of PCA is that the principal components are us=
ually linear combinations of all input variables. <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Sparse_PCA" title=3D"Sparse PCA">Sparse PCA</a> overcomes t=
his disadvantage by finding linear combinations that contain just a few inp=
ut variables. It extends the classic method of principal component analysis=
 (PCA) for the reduction of dimensionality of data by adding sparsity const=
raint on the input variables.
Several approaches have been proposed, including
</p>
<ul><li>a regression framework,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-76" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_=
note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>a convex relaxation/semidefinite programming framework,<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-SDP_77-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-SDP-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>a generalized power method framework<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analy=
sis#cite_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>an alternating maximization framework<sup id=3D"cite_ref-79" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_anal=
ysis#cite_note-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>79<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>forward-backward greedy search and exact methods using branch-and-bound=
 techniques,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-80"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
></li>
<li>Bayesian formulation framework.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-81" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#c=
ite_note-81"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>The methodological and theoretical developments of Sparse PCA as well as=
 its applications in scientific studies were recently reviewed in a survey =
paper.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Nonlinear_PCA">Nonlinear PC=
A</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_=
component_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D39" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Nonlinear PCA"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Elmap_breastcancer_wiki.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/84/Elmap_breastcance=
r_wiki.png/330px-Elmap_breastcancer_wiki.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"3=
00" height=3D"353" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"561" data-f=
ile-height=3D"661"></a><figcaption> Linear PCA versus nonlinear Principal M=
anifolds<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-83"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> fo=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_visualization" title=
=3D"Scientific visualization">visualization</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Breast_cancer" title=3D"Breast cancer">breast cancer</a> <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microarray" title=3D"Microarray">mi=
croarray</a> data: a) Configuration of nodes and 2D Principal Surface in th=
e 3D PCA linear manifold. The dataset is curved and cannot be mapped adequa=
tely on a 2D principal plane; b) The distribution in the internal 2D non-li=
near principal surface coordinates (ELMap2D) together with an estimation of=
 the density of points; c) The same as b), but for the linear 2D PCA manifo=
ld (PCA2D). The "basal" breast cancer subtype is visualized more adequately=
 with ELMap2D and some features of the distribution become better resolved =
in comparison to PCA2D. Principal manifolds are produced by the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elastic_map" title=3D"Elastic map">elastic ma=
ps</a> algorithm. Data are available for public competition.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
84<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Software is available for=
 free non-commercial use.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-8=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>Most of the modern methods for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Nonlinear_dimensionality_reduction" title=3D"Nonlinear dimensionality reduc=
tion">nonlinear dimensionality reduction</a> find their theoretical and alg=
orithmic roots in PCA or K-means. Pearson's original idea was to take a str=
aight line (or plane) which will be "the best fit" to a set of data points.=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevor_Hastie" title=3D"Trevor Ha=
stie">Trevor Hastie</a> expanded on this concept by proposing <b>Principal =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curve" title=3D"Curve">curves</a><=
/b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-86" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-86"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as the =
natural extension for the geometric interpretation of PCA, which explicitly=
 constructs a manifold for data <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ap=
proximation" title=3D"Approximation">approximation</a> followed by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Projection_(mathematics)" title=3D"Projec=
tion (mathematics)">projecting</a> the points onto it. See also the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elastic_map" title=3D"Elastic map">elasti=
c map</a> algorithm and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_=
geodesic_analysis" title=3D"Principal geodesic analysis">principal geodesic=
 analysis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-87"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Another popular generalization is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Kernel_PCA" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kernel PCA">kernel PCA</a>, =
which corresponds to PCA performed in a reproducing kernel Hilbert space as=
sociated with a positive definite kernel.
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilinear_subspace_lea=
rning" title=3D"Multilinear subspace learning">multilinear subspace learnin=
g</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Vasilescu2003_88-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-Va=
silescu2003-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Vasilescu2002tensorfaces_89-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_c=
omponent_analysis#cite_note-Vasilescu2002tensorfaces-89"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-MPCA-MICA2005_90-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-MPCA-MICA2005-90"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> PCA is generalized to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Multilinear_principal_component_analysis" title=3D"Multilinear principal c=
omponent analysis">multilinear PCA</a> (MPCA) that extracts features direct=
ly from tensor representations. MPCA is solved by performing PCA in each mo=
de of the tensor iteratively. MPCA has been applied to face recognition, ga=
it recognition, etc. MPCA is further extended to uncorrelated MPCA, non-neg=
ative MPCA and robust MPCA.
</p><p><i>N</i>-way principal component analysis may be performed with mode=
ls such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tucker_decomposition" t=
itle=3D"Tucker decomposition">Tucker decomposition</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PARAFAC" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"PARAFAC">PARA=
FAC</a>, multiple factor analysis, co-inertia analysis, STATIS, and DISTATI=
S.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Robust_PCA">Robust PCA</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DPrincipal_compon=
ent_analysis&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D40" title=3D"Edit section: Rob=
ust PCA"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>While PCA finds the mathematically optimal method (as in minimizing the =
squared error), it is still sensitive to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a> in the data that produce lar=
ge errors, something that the method tries to avoid in the first place. It =
is therefore common practice to remove outliers before computing PCA. Howev=
er, in some contexts, outliers can be difficult to identify.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-91" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis#cite_note-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
For example, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_mining" title=
=3D"Data mining">data mining</a> algorithms like <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Correlation_clustering" title=3D"Correlation clustering">cor=
relation clustering</a>, the assignment of points to clusters and outliers =
is not known beforehand.
A recently proposed generalization of PCA<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_anal=
ysis#cite_note-92"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> based on a weighted PCA increases robustness=
 by assigning different weights to data objects based on their estimated re=
levancy.
</p><p>Outlier-resistant variants of PCA have also been proposed, based on =
L1-norm formulations (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L1-norm_prin=
cipal_component_analysis" title=3D"L1-norm principal component analysis">L1=
-PCA</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mark2014_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-mark20=
14-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-mark2017_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-=
mark2017-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_principal_component_=
analysis" title=3D"Robust principal component analysis">Robust principal co=
mponent analysis</a> (RPCA) via decomposition in low-rank and sparse matric=
es is a modification of PCA that works well with respect to grossly corrupt=
ed observations.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-RPCA_93-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#cite_note-RP=
CA-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-RPCA-BOUWMANS_94-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis#ci=
te_note-RPCA-BOUWMANS-94"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-RPCA-BOUWMANS-COSR=
EV_95-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis#cite_note-RPCA-BOUWMANS-COSREV-95"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Similar_techniques">Similar=
 techniques</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
